---
import ModuleLayout from '../../layouts/ModuleLayout.astro';
import KnowledgeCheck from '../../components/KnowledgeCheck.tsx';
import ScenarioCard from '../../components/ScenarioCard.tsx';
import KeyTakeaway from '../../components/KeyTakeaway.astro';
import SegmentRevealQuiz from '../../components/SegmentRevealQuiz.tsx';
import ModelDifferentiators from '../../components/ModelDifferentiators.tsx';
import VerticalExplorer from '../../components/VerticalExplorer.tsx';
import MessageAdapter from '../../components/MessageAdapter.tsx';
import KeyConcept from '../../components/KeyConcept.astro';
import Glossary from '../../components/Glossary.astro';
import GenerativeExercise from '../../components/GenerativeExercise.tsx';

const module = {
  id: '4-player-segmentation',
  number: 4,
  title: 'Player Segmentation',
  duration: '20 min',
  lessons: [
    { title: 'A New Segmentation Model', slug: 'new-segmentation-model' },
    { title: 'Product Vertical Overlay', slug: 'product-vertical-overlay' },
    { title: 'Identifying Segments in Practice', slug: 'identifying-segments' },
    { title: 'Adapting Messages', slug: 'adapting-messages' },
  ],
};

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const tracks = [
  { slideIndex: 0, src: `${base}/audio/modules/m3-new-segmentation-model.mp3`, transcript: 'Traditional gambling segmentation groups players by demographics — age, gender, location — or by product preference — sports bettors, casino players, lottery buyers. These categories describe what people do but tell you nothing about what content they actually need. A 22-year-old and a 55-year-old who both play recreationally and understand the odds need the same content. But a sports bettor who just placed their first parlay and one who tracks the vig across 15 sportsbooks need completely different content — even though both are "sports bettors." Playbook uses a relationship-based model instead. Six segments, defined by the player\'s knowledge level, engagement pattern, and behavioral indicators. Three engagement-focused segments: New or Novice players encountering a product for the first time who need foundational education. Recreational players who play within their means with moderate knowledge and steady patterns — this is the majority of any player base. And Enthusiasts — highly engaged, deep product knowledge, they track their own play and want advanced content. Then three support-focused segments: At-Risk players showing behavioral warning signs who need tool visibility, not lectures. In-Crisis players actively seeking help who need immediate, frictionless access to support. And Friends and Family — people who aren\'t players at all, who arrive searching "how to help someone who gambles too much" and need a completely separate entry point. Three things make this model different from traditional approaches. It\'s relational, not demographic. It\'s product-contextual — a player can be Recreational in casino and New or Novice in sports simultaneously. And it\'s dynamic — players move between segments as their behavior changes. Now try the ranking exercise below to test your understanding of how these segments compare in size.' },
  { slideIndex: 1, src: `${base}/audio/modules/m3-product-vertical-overlay.mp3`, transcript: 'Segments describe who the player is in relationship to gambling. Product verticals describe what they\'re playing. These are independent dimensions that overlay each other — think of it as a grid. Playbook covers five verticals: sports betting, casino, lottery, poker, and bingo. Each has its own knowledge domains, its own misconceptions, and its own tool categories. A Recreational casino player needs session management tools and myth-busting about hot and cold machines. A Recreational sports bettor needs bankroll planning and education about vig and parlay margins. Same segment, completely different content. Without this overlay, you end up with generic content like "Know the odds!" — which is too vague for anyone to act on. Which odds? Parlay odds? Slot RTP? Lottery jackpot probability? Each requires a completely different explanation. Or you end up with product-only segments like "Sports Bettors" — which ignores that a first-time sports bettor and a five-year veteran need totally different things. The overlay gives you specificity. A New or Novice plus Sports player needs to learn what a minus-110 line means. A Recreational plus Sports player already knows that — they need bankroll planning for their NFL season. Same product, different relationships, different content. Use the Vertical Explorer tool below to see how each vertical breaks down across segments, core knowledge areas, common misconceptions, and key tool categories.' },
  { slideIndex: 2, src: `${base}/audio/modules/m3-identifying-segments.mp3`, transcript: 'You don\'t need perfect data to segment your players. Playbook uses three levels of identification that work at any level of data sophistication. Level 1 is structural identification — no data needed. Your product already tells you who\'s where. A player in onboarding? New or Novice. Browsing the sportsbook? Sports vertical. On the support page? Potentially In-Crisis. Arrived via a "worried about someone" link? Friends and Family. Structural identification isn\'t a compromise — it\'s often more accurate than predictive models because it\'s based on what players are actually doing right now. Level 2 uses basic data — account age, deposit frequency, session counts. Consistent activity over months with no escalation points to Recreational. Multi-vertical usage with high frequency suggests Enthusiast. First deposit and first session is reliably New or Novice. Level 3 is behavioral analytics — the most powerful level. With full behavioral data, you can detect At-Risk patterns: escalating deposits, chasing losses, increasing session length, repeated limit increases, late-night play spikes, and out-of-pattern behavior. No single indicator is definitive. Patterns matter. A one-time large bet during the Super Bowl is normal. A sustained increase in stake size over three weeks is a signal. Start at Level 1. Move to Level 2 when you have the data. Level 3 is a long-term goal. Now try the scenario practice exercise below — you\'ll identify the segment and vertical for eight real-world player situations.' },
  { slideIndex: 3, src: `${base}/audio/modules/m3-adapting-messages.mp3`, transcript: 'The same core message adapts to different segments by changing tone, depth, and framing — not the underlying information. The fact doesn\'t change. The lens does. Five rules govern adaptation. Same fact, different depth — New or Novice needs the definition, Recreational needs the comparison, Enthusiast needs the advanced angle. Match their language — sports bettors say "vig," poker players say "rake," casino players know "RTP." Respect what they already know — don\'t explain house edge to an Enthusiast. At-Risk and In-Crisis get tools, not education — when behavioral indicators suggest difficulty, more information isn\'t the answer. And the general voice works for most content — only adapt when the touchpoint or data demands it. Use the Message Adapter tool below to see this in action. Start with the core message "Every game has a house edge" and click each segment to see how the same truth adapts. Then add the vertical overlay to see how even a single segment\'s message changes by product. After that, you\'ll see the segment movement patterns — how players transition between segments and how your content should respond to those transitions. The most important content moments happen at these inflection points, not during steady states. Time to test what you\'ve learned.' },
  { slideIndex: 4, src: `${base}/audio/modules/m3-knowledge-check.mp3`, transcript: 'Time to test what you\'ve learned. Six questions covering the segmentation model, product vertical overlay, identifying segments, and adapting messages. You need 80 percent to mark this module complete. Take your time — several questions test the product-contextual nature of the model.' },
];

const scenarios = [
  {
    id: 's1',
    description: 'A 24-year-old signs up for a sportsbook during March Madness. They deposit $50, place a 5-leg parlay, and browse the "How do parlays work?" help article.',
    context: 'First-time sportsbook user. Arrived via a social media ad.',
    correctSegment: 'New/Novice',
    correctVertical: 'Sports',
    recommendedTone: 'Confident / Informative — they\'re actively seeking information',
    sampleMessage: '"A 5-leg parlay means all 5 picks have to hit. The odds look big, but here\'s what each leg does to your probability..."',
    explanation: 'Browsing the help article is a strong signal they\'re new to the product. Age alone doesn\'t determine segment — it\'s their relationship to THIS product that matters. They\'re a New/Novice in the Sports vertical.',
  },
  {
    id: 's2',
    description: 'A regular player logs in 3-4 times per week, plays online blackjack for 30-60 minute sessions, uses the deposit limit feature, and has been active for 8 months.',
    context: 'Consistent patterns. No escalation. Uses responsible gambling tools proactively.',
    correctSegment: 'Recreational',
    correctVertical: 'Casino',
    recommendedTone: 'Playful / Witty — they\'re comfortable and engaged',
    sampleMessage: '"You\'ve been playing for 45 minutes. Your deposit limit has $120 remaining this week. Feeling sharp or calling it?"',
    explanation: 'Consistent frequency, reasonable session length, proactive limit use, no escalation — this is a textbook Recreational player. They understand the product, manage their play, and are engaged without red flags.',
  },
  {
    id: 's3',
    description: 'Someone arrives at your site by Googling "how to help someone who gambles too much." They click on the support resources page.',
    context: 'Not a player. Arrived via search.',
    correctSegment: 'Friends & Family',
    correctVertical: 'General',
    recommendedTone: 'Warm / Direct — they\'re concerned and need clear, compassionate help',
    sampleMessage: '"You\'re here because you care about someone. That matters. Here are conversation starters, support resources, and next steps — for you."',
    explanation: 'The search query is definitive — this person isn\'t gambling, they\'re worried about someone who is. They need a completely different entry point: validation, practical tools, and resources framed for supporters, not players.',
  },
  {
    id: 's4',
    description: 'A player who\'s been active for 2 years has increased their deposit limit 3 times in 2 weeks. Their average session length has doubled and they\'re now playing at 2am regularly.',
    context: 'Established player. Behavioral data available. Rapid pattern change.',
    correctSegment: 'At-Risk',
    correctVertical: 'Casino',
    recommendedTone: 'Warm / Direct — non-judgmental, tool-focused',
    sampleMessage: '"You\'ve been playing longer than usual lately. Free, confidential support is available 24/7 — for any question about gambling."',
    explanation: 'Multiple escalation signals: repeated limit increases, doubled session length, late-night play. This isn\'t normal variation — it\'s a pattern shift. The response is non-judgmental tool visibility, not diagnosis or restriction.',
  },
  {
    id: 's5',
    description: 'A player who buys lottery tickets weekly at the same retailer enters your online lottery platform for the first time. They seem confused by the digital interface.',
    context: 'Experienced lottery player. New to online platform.',
    correctSegment: 'New/Novice',
    correctVertical: 'Lottery',
    recommendedTone: 'Confident / Informative — welcoming, not condescending',
    sampleMessage: '"Welcome to online play. Same games you know — now with instant results and a budget tracker built in. Here\'s how to get started."',
    explanation: 'This is the product-contextual nature of New/Novice. They\'re experienced with lottery as a product, but NEW to this digital platform. Their knowledge of lottery odds doesn\'t mean they understand the online interface. Meet them where they are.',
  },
  {
    id: 's6',
    description: 'A player uses your sportsbook, casino, and poker products. They know the math behind house edge, can explain parlay probability, and have a bankroll management spreadsheet.',
    context: 'Multi-vertical player. High engagement. Deep product knowledge.',
    correctSegment: 'Enthusiast',
    correctVertical: 'General',
    recommendedTone: 'Playful / Witty — respect their expertise, add depth',
    sampleMessage: '"You know the vig. You track your bankroll. But have you seen how variance plays out over 10,000 hands? Here\'s the simulation."',
    explanation: 'Deep knowledge across multiple products, proactive bankroll management, high engagement — Enthusiast. Don\'t teach them basics. Offer advanced content that respects their expertise and adds genuine value.',
  },
  {
    id: 's7',
    description: 'A player clicks "I need help" on your site, then navigates to the self-exclusion page and starts the process.',
    context: 'Active player. Self-initiated help-seeking.',
    correctSegment: 'In-Crisis',
    correctVertical: 'General',
    recommendedTone: 'Warm / Direct (serious) — zero friction, zero cleverness',
    sampleMessage: '"We\'re here. Your account can be paused right now. You can also call [helpline] — free, confidential, 24/7."',
    explanation: 'Clicking "I need help" and starting self-exclusion is unambiguous. This is Tier 2 territory. The response must be immediate, frictionless, and completely devoid of marketing or cleverness. Speed and clarity are everything.',
  },
  {
    id: 's8',
    description: 'A player who typically bets $10-20 on NFL games suddenly places a $500 single bet on a Champions League match in a sport they\'ve never bet on before.',
    context: 'Sportsbook player. Sudden behavior change. Single incident.',
    correctSegment: 'At-Risk',
    correctVertical: 'Sports',
    recommendedTone: 'Warm / Direct — a gentle check-in, not an alarm',
    sampleMessage: '"This bet is larger than your usual. No judgment — just a heads up. Your deposit limit tools are here if you want them."',
    explanation: 'A single incident isn\'t definitive, but the combination of factors — 25x typical stake, unfamiliar sport, out-of-pattern behavior — warrants a check-in. At-Risk doesn\'t mean "in crisis." It means behavioral indicators suggest monitoring and gentle tool visibility.',
  },
];

const questions = [
  {
    id: 'q1',
    question: 'What is the fundamental basis for Playbook\'s segmentation model?',
    options: [
      'Demographics — age, gender, location',
      'Product preference — which games they play',
      'Relationship to gambling — knowledge level, engagement patterns, and behavioral indicators',
      'Spending level — how much they deposit',
    ],
    correctIndex: 2,
    explanation: 'Playbook segments by relationship to gambling, not demographics or product choice, but a 22-year-old and a 55-year-old who both play casually and understand the odds are both Recreational players. Demographics don\'t determine how to communicate with someone — their relationship to the activity does.',
    reviewSlug: 'new-segmentation-model',
  },
  {
    id: 'q2',
    question: 'A loyal lottery player of 10 years signs up for your new sportsbook product. What segment are they for sports betting content?',
    options: [
      'Recreational — they\'re an experienced gambler',
      'Enthusiast — they clearly love gambling if they\'re adding products',
      'New/Novice — they\'re new to THIS specific product',
      'At-Risk — adding a new product could signal escalation',
    ],
    correctIndex: 2,
    explanation: 'New/Novice is product-contextual. This player knows lottery well (probably Recreational or Enthusiast for lottery) but is a genuine novice for sports betting. They need sports-specific education: how betting lines work, what vig means, how parlays multiply risk. Their lottery experience doesn\'t transfer.',
    reviewSlug: 'product-vertical-overlay',
  },
  {
    id: 'q3',
    question: 'What is the relationship between segments and product verticals in Playbook\'s model?',
    options: [
      'Each vertical has its own set of segments',
      'Segments and verticals are the same thing',
      'Segments describe the player\'s relationship; verticals describe what they play — they overlay independently',
      'Verticals only matter for New/Novice players',
    ],
    correctIndex: 2,
    explanation: 'Think of it as a grid: segments on one axis (who they are in relationship to gambling), verticals on the other (what product they\'re using). A Recreational Sports Bettor needs different content than a Recreational Casino player — same relationship, different product context.',
    reviewSlug: 'product-vertical-overlay',
  },
  {
    id: 'q4',
    question: 'How should you handle a player who is an Enthusiast in casino but has just started using your sportsbook?',
    options: [
      'Treat them as an Enthusiast across all products',
      'Treat them as New/Novice across all products',
      'Enthusiast for casino touchpoints, New/Novice for sportsbook touchpoints',
      'Ask them to complete a knowledge quiz to determine their segment',
    ],
    correctIndex: 2,
    explanation: 'Segments can differ by vertical. On your casino product, respect their expertise and offer advanced content. On your sportsbook, they need the basics — what vig is, how lines work, why parlays are risky. Don\'t assume knowledge transfers between verticals.',
    reviewSlug: 'adapting-messages',
  },
  {
    id: 'q5',
    question: 'What distinguishes At-Risk from In-Crisis?',
    options: [
      'At-Risk players lose more money',
      'At-Risk shows behavioral indicators suggesting players in difficulty; In-Crisis is actively seeking help or showing severe distress',
      'They\'re the same segment with different names',
      'At-Risk is identified by operators; In-Crisis is self-identified',
    ],
    correctIndex: 1,
    explanation: 'At-Risk is a Tier 1/2 boundary — behavioral indicators suggest patterns may be non-rational, and the response is increased tool visibility and gentle check-ins. In-Crisis is firmly Tier 2 — the player is in distress or actively seeking support, and the response is immediate, frictionless access to help.',
    reviewSlug: 'new-segmentation-model',
  },
  {
    id: 'q6',
    question: 'When should you use segment-specific messaging instead of the general Playbook voice?',
    options: [
      'Always — every piece of content should target a specific segment',
      'Only for At-Risk and In-Crisis players',
      'When the touchpoint is inherently segment-specific, a campaign targets one segment, or behavioral data identifies a segment',
      'Never — the general voice works for everyone',
    ],
    correctIndex: 2,
    explanation: 'The general Playbook voice is your default — it works for everyone. Adapt only when the touchpoint inherently serves a segment (a parlay builder = sports vertical), a campaign deliberately targets one group, or behavioral data triggers a segment match. Most content doesn\'t need segment-specific adaptation.',
    reviewSlug: 'adapting-messages',
  },
];
---

<ModuleLayout module={module} panelMode={true} tracks={tracks}>

  <!-- Module intro -->
  <div class="mb-8 p-5 rounded-xl bg-navy/5 border border-navy/10">
    <p class="text-sm text-navy font-heading mb-2">
      <strong>Player Segmentation</strong> — A relationship-based segmentation model, product vertical overlay, identifying segments in practice, and adapting messages.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-navy mb-3 font-heading"><strong>By the end of this module, you will be able to:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-sm text-n700 mb-4 space-y-1.5 pl-4 list-disc">
      <li>Name the six Playbook segments and explain why segmentation is product-contextual</li>
      <li>Apply the five product verticals to any player scenario</li>
      <li>Identify a player's segment from behavioral data and adapt messaging accordingly</li>
    </ul>
    <button
      id="start-narration-btn"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 bg-teal text-navy font-heading font-bold rounded-lg hover:bg-teal-light transition-colors text-sm"
    >
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M8 5v14l11-7z"/></svg>
      Play Audio Guide
    </button>
  </div>

  <script>
    document.getElementById('start-narration-btn')?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('start-playback'));
    });
  </script>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 4.1: A New Segmentation Model           -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="new-segmentation-model" data-slide-index="0" data-lesson-slug="new-segmentation-model" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>A New Segmentation Model</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      Traditional gambling industry segmentation groups players by demographics (age, gender) or product (sports bettors, casino players, lottery buyers). This creates segments that describe <em>what</em> people do, but not <em>how they relate to gambling</em> — which is what actually determines what content they need.
    </p>

    <p>
      A 22-year-old and a 55-year-old who both play recreationally and understand the odds need the same content but a "sports bettor" who just placed their first parlay and one who tracks vig across 15 sportsbooks need completely different content. Demographics and product choice don't tell you what someone needs — their relationship to gambling does.
    </p>

    <p>
      Playbook uses a <strong>relationship-based segmentation model</strong>. Six segments, defined by the player's knowledge, engagement pattern, and behavioral indicators.
    </p>

    <h3 id="the-six-segments">The six segments</h3>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Segment</th>
          <th>Relationship</th>
          <th>What they need</th>
          <th>Tone</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>New / Novice</strong></td>
          <td>Low knowledge of a specific product. Recently started or encountering a product for the first time.</td>
          <td>How the product works, what the numbers mean, where risks exist. Foundational education.</td>
          <td>Confident / Informative</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Recreational</strong></td>
          <td>Plays within means, moderate-to-good knowledge, steady patterns. The majority of players.</td>
          <td>Engagement, not education. Myth-busting, social content, tools framed as features.</td>
          <td>Playful / Witty</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Enthusiast</strong></td>
          <td>High engagement, deep product knowledge, tracks their own play. Not problematic — just highly engaged.</td>
          <td>Advanced content, new perspectives, community. Respect their expertise.</td>
          <td>Playful / Witty (peer level)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>The three support-focused segments:</strong></p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Segment</th>
          <th>Relationship</th>
          <th>What they need</th>
          <th>Tone</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>At-Risk</strong></td>
          <td>Behavioral indicators suggest players in difficulty. Escalating patterns.</td>
          <td>Non-judgmental tool visibility, check-in moments, accessible support.</td>
          <td>Warm / Direct</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>In-Crisis</strong></td>
          <td>Actively seeking help or showing severe distress. Tier 2 territory.</td>
          <td>Immediate, frictionless access to support. Zero barriers.</td>
          <td>Warm / Direct (serious)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Friends & Family</strong></td>
          <td>Not a player. Concerned about someone else's gambling.</td>
          <td>Separate entry point. Conversation starters, support resources, validation.</td>
          <td>Warm / Direct</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <SegmentRevealQuiz client:visible />

    <h3 id="what-makes-this-model-different">What makes this model different</h3>

    <ModelDifferentiators client:visible />

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>
        Most Playbook content works for all segments without modification. The general voice is your default. Segment-specific adaptation is for targeted campaigns, segment-specific touchpoints, or when behavioral data identifies a match.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 4.2: Product Vertical Overlay            -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="product-vertical-overlay" data-slide-index="1" data-lesson-slug="product-vertical-overlay" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>Product Vertical Overlay</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      Segments describe <em>who</em> the player is in relationship to gambling. Product verticals describe <em>what</em> they're playing. These are independent dimensions that overlay each other.
    </p>

    <p>
      Think of it as a grid:
    </p>

    <VerticalExplorer client:visible />

    <h3 id="why-the-overlay-matters">Why the overlay matters</h3>

    <p>
      Without the overlay, you end up with either:
    </p>

    <div class="list-card">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Generic content</strong> — "Know the odds!" — that's too vague for anyone to act on. <em>Which</em> odds? Parlay odds? Slot RTP? Lottery jackpot probability? Each requires completely different explanations.</li>
        <li><strong>Product-only segments</strong> — "Sports Bettors" as a segment — that ignores a first-time sports bettor and a 5-year veteran need totally different things, even though they use the same product.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>
      The overlay gives you specificity. A <strong>New/Novice + Sports</strong> player needs to learn what a -110 line means. A <strong>Recreational + Sports</strong> player already knows that — they need bankroll planning for their NFL season. Same product, different relationships, different content.
    </p>

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>
        The segment-vertical overlay gives you specificity that neither dimension provides alone. A player's relationship to gambling tells you how to communicate; the product vertical tells you what to communicate about.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 4.3: Identifying Segments in Practice    -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="identifying-segments" data-slide-index="2" data-lesson-slug="identifying-segments" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>Identifying Segments in Practice</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      You don't need perfect data to segment your players. Playbook uses three levels of identification that work at any level of data sophistication.
    </p>

    <h3 id="level-1-structural-identification-no-data-needed">Level 1: Structural identification (no data needed)</h3>

    <p>
      Your product already tells you who's where. You just need to read the signals:
    </p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Signal</th>
          <th>What it tells you</th>
          <th>Segment + Vertical</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Player is in onboarding / first session</td>
          <td>They're new to your product</td>
          <td><strong>New/Novice</strong> + whatever vertical they're using</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Player is browsing the sportsbook</td>
          <td>They're engaging with sports betting</td>
          <td>Sports vertical (segment depends on other signals)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Player is on the support / helpline page</td>
          <td>They may be seeking help</td>
          <td><strong>In-Crisis</strong> (or information-seeking — context matters)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Visitor arrived via "worried about someone" link</td>
          <td>They're a concerned other, not a player</td>
          <td><strong>Friends & Family</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Player is browsing "How to play" content</td>
          <td>They're learning the product</td>
          <td><strong>New/Novice</strong> for that product</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <blockquote>
      <p>Structural identification isn't a compromise — it's often more accurate than behavioral models because it's based on what players are actually doing, not what a model predicts they'll do.</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h3 id="level-2-basic-data-registration-activity">Level 2: Basic data (registration + activity)</h3>

    <p>
      With basic data — account age, deposit frequency, session counts, product usage — you can infer more:
    </p>

    <div class="list-card">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Account age + consistent activity → Recreational.</strong> Someone who's been playing steadily for months with no escalation is likely Recreational.</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-vertical usage + high frequency → potential Enthusiast.</strong> Regular play across multiple products, especially with proactive tool use, suggests deep engagement.</li>
        <li><strong>First deposit + first session → New/Novice.</strong> The most reliable signal. If they just signed up, they're new to your platform regardless of their experience elsewhere.</li>
        <li><strong>Referral from support search → Friends & Family.</strong> A visitor arriving via "gambling help for families" is almost certainly a concerned other.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3 id="level-3-behavioral-analytics">Level 3: Behavioral analytics</h3>

    <p>
      With full behavioral data — play patterns, session trends, limit-setting history, content engagement — you unlock the most important capability: <strong>At-Risk detection</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Behavioral indicators for At-Risk:
    </p>

    <div class="list-card">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Escalating deposits</strong> — spending more over time, especially after losses</li>
        <li><strong>Chasing losses</strong> — increasing bets to recover previous losses</li>
        <li><strong>Increasing session length and frequency</strong> — playing longer and more often than their baseline</li>
        <li><strong>Repeated limit increases</strong> — raising self-imposed limits shortly after hitting them</li>
        <li><strong>Late-night play spikes</strong> — sessions shifting to unusual hours</li>
        <li><strong>Out-of-pattern behavior</strong> — sudden changes in stake size, product, or frequency</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>
      <strong>No single indicator is definitive.</strong> Patterns matter. A one-time large bet during the Super Bowl is normal. A sustained increase in stake size over 3 weeks is a signal. Context is everything.
    </p>

    <KeyTakeaway title="Start where you are">
      <p>
        Start at Level 1. Move to Level 2 when you have the data. Level 3 is a long-term goal. Most operators launch successfully with structural identification alone — your product touchpoints already tell you more than you think.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>

    <h3 id="scenario-practice-heading">Scenario practice</h3>

    <p>
      Apply what you've learned. For each scenario, identify the relationship segment and product vertical.
    </p>

    <ScenarioCard client:visible scenarios={scenarios} />
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 4.4: Adapting Messages                   -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="adapting-messages" data-slide-index="3" data-lesson-slug="adapting-messages" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>Adapting Messages by Segment</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      The same core message adapts to different segments by changing tone, depth, and framing — not the underlying information. The fact doesn't change. The lens does.
    </p>

    <h3 id="rules-for-adapting">Rules for adapting</h3>

    <ol class="space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Same fact, different depth.</strong> New/Novice needs the definition. Recreational needs the comparison. Enthusiast needs the advanced angle. The underlying truth is identical.</li>
      <li><strong>Match their language.</strong> Sports bettors say "vig," not "house edge." Poker players say "rake." Casino players know "RTP." Use the vocabulary of their vertical.</li>
      <li><strong>Respect what they already know.</strong> Don't explain house edge to an Enthusiast. Don't explain basic odds to someone who's been playing for 3 years. Add to their knowledge, don't start from zero.</li>
      <li><strong>At-Risk and In-Crisis get tools, not education.</strong> When behavioral indicators suggest players in difficulty, more information isn't the answer. Tool visibility and support access are.</li>
      <li><strong>The general voice works for most content.</strong> Only adapt when the touchpoint, campaign, or behavioral data demands it. Your default is always the general Playbook voice.</li>
    </ol>

    <MessageAdapter client:visible />

    <GenerativeExercise
      client:visible
      title="Write a Segment-Adapted Message"
      context="Your operator is launching a new 'Game IQ' quiz feature. You need to write the notification that appears when a Recreational casino player completes the quiz and scores 8/10."
      prompt="Write the notification message (1-2 sentences). Think about: what register fits this moment? What does a Recreational player value? How do you acknowledge achievement without being over-the-top?"
      rubric={[
        { label: 'Correct register', description: 'Celebratory — this is an achievement moment for an engaged player' },
        { label: 'Segment-appropriate depth', description: 'Recreational players value fun and social proof, not deep technical detail' },
        { label: 'References a specific outcome', description: 'Mentions the score, the achievement, or what they learned — not generic praise' },
        { label: 'No prescriptive language', description: 'No "you should" or "make sure to" — agency framing only' },
      ]}
      modelAnswer="8 out of 10 — you know your games. Your Game IQ just leveled up. Share your score or try the next quiz when you're ready."
    />

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>
        Adapt the lens, not the fact. The same core message changes by tone, depth, and vocabulary depending on the segment and vertical — but the underlying truth stays constant. And remember: the general Playbook voice is your default for most content.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- LESSON 4.5: Segment Movement Patterns           -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="segment-movement-patterns" data-slide-index="3" data-lesson-slug="adapting-messages" class="module-section py-16">
    <h3 id="segment-movement-patterns-heading">Segment movement patterns</h3>

    <p>
      Segments aren't permanent labels — they describe where a player is <em>right now</em>, not who they are. Players move between segments as their knowledge grows, their habits change, or life circumstances shift. Your content strategy needs to account for these transitions, not just the states themselves.
    </p>

    <p>
      Each transition has a <strong>trigger</strong> (the behavioral signal that tells you something is changing) and a <strong>content response</strong> (how your messaging should adapt). The goal is to meet the player where they're heading, not where they were.
    </p>

    <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 my-6">
      <KeyConcept title="New/Novice → Recreational" icon="trending-up">
        <p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Time + knowledge. The player learns how the product works, develops consistent patterns.</p>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> Gradually reduce "how it works" content. Introduce engagement content, myth-busting, social features.</p>
      </KeyConcept>
      <KeyConcept title="Recreational → Enthusiast" icon="microscope">
        <p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Deepening engagement, increasing knowledge, multi-vertical exploration.</p>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> Offer advanced content. Don't repeat basics. Treat them as a peer, not a student.</p>
      </KeyConcept>
      <KeyConcept title="Any → At-Risk" icon="alert-triangle">
        <p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Behavioral indicators: escalating deposits, chasing losses, increasing frequency, repeated limit changes.</p>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> Increase tool visibility. Gentle check-ins. Make support one tap away. Never label or diagnose.</p>
      </KeyConcept>
      <KeyConcept title="At-Risk → In-Crisis" icon="alert-circle">
        <p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Self-identification (clicking "I need help"), self-exclusion initiation, severe behavioral patterns.</p>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> Tier 2 response. Zero friction. Zero cleverness. Immediate access to support.</p>
      </KeyConcept>
      <KeyConcept title="At-Risk → Recreational" icon="check-circle">
        <p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Patterns stabilize. Behavior returns to baseline. Tools are working.</p>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> Quietly reduce check-in frequency. Don't celebrate or reference the risk period. Resume normal content.</p>
      </KeyConcept>
    </div>

    <p>
      Notice that movement is <strong>not always forward</strong>. A Recreational player who encounters a stressful life event may shift toward At-Risk, then return to Recreational when things stabilize. An Enthusiast who tries a new product vertical drops back to New/Novice for that specific product. The model is fluid by design — it responds to behavior, not biography.
    </p>

    <KeyTakeaway title="Design for transitions">
      <p>
        The most important content moments happen during segment transitions — when a New/Novice is becoming Recreational, or when a Recreational player starts showing At-Risk signals. Build content for these inflection points, not just steady states. If you only have content for "where they are," you'll always be one step behind.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

